# Presentation Slide Rules

## For agents (figure discovery)

- **Figures are not "text only"** - `presentation.tex` references them by **filename** via `\includegraphics{...}`. The search order is set by `\graphicspath` in the preamble: `Extracted_figures/`, then `Paper_files/`, then `Assets/`, then the repo root.
- **When a figure seems missing** - list or glob `Paper_files/` for `*.png`, `*.jpg`, `*.pdf` (and similar). The author is expected to place paper-derived figures **next to the paper** in `Paper_files/`, not only in the `.tex` prose. Do not assume the only source of truth is the written slide text; the file system in `Paper_files/` is canonical for "what we have from the paper."
- **After `beamer_to_pptx.py` runs** - copies of used figures land in `Extracted_figures/`. If that folder is empty or incomplete, the originals are still under `Paper_files/`.
- **Embedded images inside the paper PDF** are not auto-extracted; the human (or a dedicated export step) must save them as files into `Paper_files/` before they can be `\includegraphics`d by filename.

## Project layout

- `presentation.tex` - main Beamer source. `\graphicspath` is `{Extracted_figures/}{Paper_files/}{Assets/}`, so figures are referenced by filename only and found in either the paper folder or the copies the converter makes.
- `Paper_files/` - the paper being presented AND any figures the user pulls out of it (PDF / tex / PNG / JPG / supplementary). **User-populated; starts empty.** This is the one place the user drops figure files.
- `Extracted_figures/` - **populated by the converter, not by the user; starts empty**:
  - `beamer_to_pptx.py` copies every `\includegraphics` source file into this folder so the deck's figure set is self-contained and archivable.
  - Auto-cropped TikZ/table PNGs also land here as `slide_content_<N>.png` (git-ignored).
  - Do not instruct users to hand-copy files into this folder; the converter does it.
- `Assets/` - logo, banner, and any reusable graphics. The footer logo defaults to `Assets/logo.jpg` and is **not** copied into `Extracted_figures/` (it's chrome, not slide content).
- `beamer_to_pptx.py` - single-script converter: `.tex` (+ optional `.pdf`) into an editable `.pptx`. Copies referenced figures into `Extracted_figures/` and writes its TikZ/table crops there too.

## Formatting

- **Bold as leading labels only**: Use `\textbf{Label}:` at the start of bullets. Never bold mid-sentence.
- **Consistent bold**: Every bullet in a slide must follow the same pattern. If one bullet has a bold label, all bullets on that slide should too.
- **No em dashes**: Do not use `---` (em dash). Use commas, semicolons, or colons instead.

## Content

- **Tight bullets (AI editing `presentation.tex`)**: You **must** keep each body `\item` **short** (one line on 16:9 when possible; no paragraph-style items). You **must** put paragraphs of detail in `\note{...}` after `\end{frame}`, or split into sub-bullets. Long bullets mean the slide is doing the speaker's job; the slide headlines, the notes explain.
- **Concise bullets**: Keep slides readable. If a slide feels overwhelming, trim content or split into sub-bullets.
- **Sub-bullets for multi-part points**: Break compound ideas into sub-bullets rather than one long sentence.
- **Speaker notes are default**: Every frame must be followed by a `\note{...}` block on the line immediately after `\end{frame}`. The converter reads these and writes them to the PPTX Notes pane.
- **Speaker notes as bullets**: Use bullet-like phrasing in `\note{...}` when transitioning between topics or when it improves clarity.
- **Explain abbreviations**: When an abbreviation appears in `\note{...}`, spell it out in parentheses on first use (e.g., "CNN (Convolutional Neural Network)").
- **Avoid overly bold claims**: Soften absolute language (e.g., "do not target" instead of "none target").
- **Lead with top results**: In results slides, highlight the best-performing model first, not baselines or outliers.
- **Include key variable comparisons** on each results slide where relevant (e.g., frame rate differences).
- **Remove distracting outliers**: Omit odd or unrepresentative data points that distract from the main message.

## Layout

- **Image beside text**: Use `\begin{columns}[T]` with left column ~0.50\textwidth (text) and right column ~0.47\textwidth (figure). Do not place figures below text.
- **Text above footer**: Keep body text from overlapping the footer. Use `\vspace{-0.4em}` at frame start; limit figure height (e.g., `height=0.58\textheight`); use `{\small ...}` for dense slides.
- **Figures by filename only**: Because of `\graphicspath`, write `\includegraphics{figure1}` rather than `\includegraphics{Paper_files/figure1}` or `\includegraphics{Extracted_figures/figure1}`. Let the converter handle the copy.

## Style

- **Sub-bullet color**: All bullet levels must use the same accent color. Override Beamer defaults if needed.
- **Logo default**: The footer logo is enabled by default (`\renewcommand{\mylogo}{...}` uncommented) and points to `Assets/logo.jpg`. Prefer JPG for the footer logo when available.
- **Slide naming**: Use descriptive, audience-friendly titles (e.g., "Situation recognition" over "Factor prediction").

## Tables and TikZ

- The converter falls back to image rasterization for `\begin{tabular}` and `\begin{tikzpicture}`.
- Cropping is driven by the PDF's vector drawings (booktabs rule lines, TikZ paths) and embedded image rects, not by whitespace heuristics. Keep surrounding captions / bullet text out of the same horizontal band as the table so the clip stays tight.
- When a table shares a slide with bullet text, the converter snaps the crop to the table's bottom rule line - do not place explanatory prose immediately under a table that is meant to be extracted as an image; put it in `\note{...}` or in a separate frame.

## Workflow

1. Edit `presentation.tex` (with a `\note{...}` after every `\end{frame}`).
2. Compile PDF: `latexmk -pdf -interaction=nonstopmode presentation.tex`.
3. Build PPTX: `python3 beamer_to_pptx.py presentation.tex`.

Always recompile the PDF after `.tex` changes before rebuilding the PPTX - the converter uses the PDF for high-fidelity cropping of tables and TikZ.
